1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:19,000
My name is Emily Crosby and I'm here this morning on December 1, 2015 with Mrs. Jeanette Smith and Mrs. Rolani Branch.

3
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:27,000
And we're at the University of Southern Mississippi Center for Oil History and Cultural Heritage, which has been helping with these interviews.

4
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:37,000
And this interview is part of the Civil Rights History Project, co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

5
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:41,000
So good morning and welcome and thank you. Good morning, good morning.

6
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:49,000
Thank you. I wonder if we could start if you could each just say a little bit about when you were born, where you were born and your family?

7
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:52,000
I guess you're starting this move.

8
00:00:53,000 --> 00:01:02,000
I was born in Jones County, free state of Jones. I was born January 1, 1940.

9
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:12,000
And basically I have property up there now, I have the family property. So my heritage is deep there.

10
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:18,000
And eventually I would like to move back to So-So.

11
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:38,000
It has so many fun memories. I had one of my parents. They really raised us right. And on the circumstances being a product of the free state of Jones, parents didn't teach us to hate anyone.

12
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:46,000
And that was a good thing for me, especially going through the movement.

13
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:56,000
I stayed in Jacksonville a while, two years, then I moved back to So-So, finished high school and met my husband.

14
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:04,000
I married him and moved to your dad's birth in 1959, January.

15
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:10,000
You know, not everybody's going to know about the free state of Jones. Can you tell us about that?

16
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:22,000
Captain Newton Knight was able to meet my great-great-grandmother Rachel, his grandfather, and bought her as a slave.

17
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:32,000
He fell in love with her. And he figured that he would just establish his own state. He didn't believe in segregation.

18
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:42,000
He married her, and he had a family by her. And my grandfather was a proud of that family.

19
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:54,000
So he wasn't successful in establishing his free state of Jones. So he deserted the Confederacy and joined the union.

20
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:02,000
He succeeded differently if I'm like a Confederacy. He succeeded. And there is a movie coming out.

21
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:14,000
And in general, about it, Dr. Biden was doing like you. She wrote a book on the free state of Jones.

22
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:18,000
And what that book does, it documents my people.

23
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:22,000
So in Mississippi, where we think of things as sort of black and white, right?

24
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:24,000
It was never black and white.

25
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:30,000
And I think this area is one of the places that really shows some of the complexity of that.

26
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:39,000
Yeah, all right. They did. And then that's one reason because the mixture of the races, that's why black people have so much life.

27
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:42,000
Because they gave all of you a rematch.

28
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:46,000
And that's the land that's still there.

29
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:56,000
But it comes from my mother's side, which is the same type of situation.

30
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:08,000
My grandfather was Indian and white. And you know, just a mixture of both sides by racial people.

31
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:12,000
What kind of work did your family do in your parents?

32
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:18,000
My mother was the black nurse. And my father was a contractor, a carpenter.

33
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:30,000
And he did farm and he had his own land. He was hired out. He'd build a lot of all-so and the helicopter homes there for the doctors and lawyers and people like that.

34
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
It was independent.

35
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:39,000
I want to come back and follow up with Ms. Branch. Could you tell us about why you were born in your family?

36
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:49,000
I was born the first of September, 1941. We're of the same age group.

37
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:57,000
I was born here in Hattiesburg, 7-11 Whitney Street in my grandmother's house.

38
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:05,000
It was a three-room shotgun house with outdoor pretty.

39
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:11,000
We had sidewalks. So at that time you paid for them if you wanted to get sidewalks and families.

40
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:15,000
Did you pay the city or did you pay somebody for the rent?

41
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:19,000
You paid the city and they installed.

42
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:25,000
So the street on which I was born had a church on the corner.

43
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:39,000
Miss Emma Campbell, who I don't know where Miss Emma came from, but Miss Emma was even lighter in skin color than Jeanette.

44
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:45,000
And Mr. Kelly, I think, was some way tied up in that.

45
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:55,000
There are several little communities around Hattiesburg where there were situations like Jeanette's parents.

46
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:59,000
And they had children.

47
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:09,000
I was born here in Hattiesburg. I had one brother born here in Hattiesburg even though they're 10 of us, 10 children.

48
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:20,000
And I too come from family out around Prentice, Mississippi, a little village called Mount Carmel, Mississippi.

49
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:26,000
And we went back and looked at the books and my great grandparents actually bought that property.

50
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:34,000
40 acres. Each one, they bought 80 acres. Nobody gave that 40 acres in a mule.

51
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:43,000
That never, never was a true thing. It might have been on the books, but it wasn't something that actually happened.

52
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:57,000
But land was divided up in 40 acres. I lived between Hattiesburg and Mount Carmel, with the school between Hattiesburg and Mount Carmel.

53
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:06,000
And I'm a person who, I would say I would beg to differ with you about the civil rights history.

54
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:16,000
They're really, we are making history today because civil rights is still a problem. We're a wife.

55
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:29,000
And I don't believe in different races of mankind. We're all mankind. We're not all men, but we're all mankind.

56
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:38,000
I would love to have it before I die, where people are like Jeanette and I.

57
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:50,000
We were never taught to hate people because when you went to a funeral, there were blonde and blue eyed people there who were your closest of kids.

58
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:59,000
So you grew up with this in your head and I really never knew a difference until the death of Emma Jill.

59
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:11,000
And that I was in Chicago at that time. I was a teenager. And up until then, just did not realize the hatred and hate.

60
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:32,000
I knew there were differing communities, but the lady who lived next to my great grandmother, who was married to a gentleman who did not have, but since I would say he drank and he didn't take care of his family properly.

61
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:41,000
He didn't farm properly. And she was what we call today white Caucasian of European extraction.

62
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:58,000
Po white folks, some folks call them. Po crackers, some people call them. But she would come over and help my great grandmother get food in and can and pee, shell.

63
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:09,000
So my great grandmother would give food and meat to her to take the feed the host of young ones as they say that she had.

64
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:23,000
I husband was no good, but she would come and help my great grandmother. So I grew up not really understanding because there were situations like that.

65
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:32,000
Was that kind of interaction in community? Was that the same in town as it was out in the country?

66
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:50,000
I think in town, women of color worked in the big houses, in the houses. And it was many times. It was a reciprocal relationship.

67
00:09:50,000 --> 00:10:00,000
You were able to carry home the food that was left over, the clothes that were too little left over when you wanted to buy a house,

68
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:15,000
Miss Ann could call the bank or her husband could call the bank and say, you know, give, give, give, give soons on so that long for that house.

69
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:34,000
So there were there were relationships. But the badness was there. I think I think the movie, the help, tells the story better than anything I've ever seen.

70
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:43,000
It's for the meanness. What kind of work did your parents do? My father was a farmer.

71
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:58,000
He died when I was 14 and he died in Chicago. He thought he couldn't get a job. There were no jobs. You can be hired out by someone.

72
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:08,000
I can remember picking cotton, sitting on what they call a slide pulled by a mule from one field to another.

73
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:25,000
And my mother was a housewife. We went to Chicago. In Chicago my father worked at the first job he had was tip-top bakery. And I'm sure it was just scrap work.

74
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:49,000
My mother's first job I remember was at Brock Candy Company. And my mother was so fair they hired her thinking she was white. And she didn't have better sense than to go sit and have lunch with the person, the one woman in the building who was color.

75
00:11:49,000 --> 00:12:11,000
She would go and sit and have lunch and finally the supervisor said to her one day, why do you go sit with her and have lunch? And that inward. And my mother said because I'm one of those. And she was fired on the spot.

76
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:25,000
And I would have kept the job to help feed my children because we lived much better in Mississippi than we ever did in Chicago.

77
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:36,000
Was that because you could raise your food? You had land, you could raise your food. You had relatives.

78
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:43,000
You had family and everybody in town was kin one way or the other.

79
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:52,000
I was going to ask what it was like for you to move to Chicago from Mississippi.

80
00:12:52,000 --> 00:13:07,000
It wasn't that much different as a child. There were very few children of European extraction in my class, very few.

81
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:18,000
There were none here except all of those little high yellow ones that were moved or even the blonde green-eyed cousins.

82
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:33,000
But it was much different. When we went to Oak Park outside of Chicago or Wineca Illinois on the train, the school would take you on the school trip.

83
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:38,000
You would go on the L train and just ride so far and get off and come back.

84
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:47,000
And you would see all these big beautiful homes and communities.

85
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:55,000
But you didn't internalize it as something against you. You just figured that your parents couldn't afford it.

86
00:13:55,000 --> 00:14:04,000
But we did own our home in Chicago. My dad had bought a home. In fact, he bought two and he got sick.

87
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:16,000
He had some type of blood dyscracia. And my mother was pregnant and we lost our home and we ended up in the park homeless furniture in the alley.

88
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:21,000
What did your family do?

89
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:29,000
We lived in the park for a while. We were just homeless folks trying to find some place to sleep at night.

90
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:36,000
And that was usually one room and everybody piled into that one room.

91
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:42,000
I would never take my children back to a city.

92
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:49,000
This is a city. But I'm now able to own and buy and sell.

93
00:14:49,000 --> 00:15:01,000
But I would not. People. I see people in, let's say, out of Africa and out of the Middle East trying to get to Europe.

94
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:08,000
Some are getting there and finding out the streets are not paid with gold.

95
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:17,000
And it's better at home. Even if you had to mash the corn by hand, it's better at home.

96
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:30,000
I want to come back to what you said about Hamid Till. But first I was wondering if you could both tell me some of the things that you learned in school and from your families that you think were important.

97
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:42,000
I grew up in a family, seven-year-old, seven-year-old, we had our own school. We were called the lightning girl.

98
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:50,000
Even though our relatives were dark, you had to fight racism within both races.

99
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:57,000
And you had the terrorists that clook up clean. It was just that we were descendants of Newton Night.

100
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:04,000
So it didn't know about a father, a note. Because he didn't take no stuff he didn't bother with people.

101
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:17,000
But when my mother married my daddy, they called him a scrooge, and I'm crazy, he said, my children are going to public school.

102
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:29,000
We're not going to isolate them. They got to live in a real world. They got to live with their relatives, some of my daughter, and some of her alike.

103
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:40,000
We didn't have anything to do with this. So what we're going to do, we're going to live within what's going on. You're going to accept what's going on.

104
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:52,000
You're not going to have any hatred against people that are dark upon you and white people. You're going to live in a real world. You're going to love everybody.

105
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:58,000
My people were Christian people. They didn't believe in hatred and stuff like that.

106
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:08,000
And if you open-minded and our people had traveled, and I had never traveled that much, but I did.

107
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:19,000
But I had relatives who had been everywhere. And we're very important people. And you have struggles of terrorists that are going on from the beginning of time.

108
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:28,000
That's why I'm just so appalled that I'm making such an issue on these immigrants.

109
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:43,000
You know, to me as a little girl, I always wonder, how can they come in here and take this country from any slaughtered him and kill him in this their country?

110
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:59,000
Then I found out, California, they did the same thing. It's just people that conquered. And then my mother would teach me to read the Bible. It was going on back then. Same thing, brother guess what?

111
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:12,000
That's saying in the world that has nothing to do. They don't even know why they don't. So then as a little girl, I ask, I have so many questions.

112
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:31,000
Why would this man know that it was illegal? Married as well as she was a mixed woman. Married her and tried to establish his own country and bring about children that are going to be faced with all this hatred among both races.

113
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:53,000
You're not accepted anywhere. So I remember growing up, the street you see now, I had them all done. But I tended. I tended my hair just as soon as I could. I got along because my mother, my first cousin had a beauty college. I brought about Jackson State. So I learned how to cover it up.

114
00:18:53,000 --> 00:19:07,000
I thought of myself. I look pole cat. I'm just strict. I'm just messed up. And then my mother would get on my case. Why? You ask all this person. I said, well, my mom just wanted to know.

115
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:20,000
She said, we don't talk about that. We're trying to out legal that. I don't want you to go back in the past. You know, you didn't have anything to do with being more. You're a God's job.

116
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:46,000
So I kept pounding on there. I'm gotcha. I don't feel it having me feeling sorry to anyone. I get along with everyone. Those are just problems of the world. You've got terrorists all over the world. If I know, look me silly. Over there in Israel, it's not enough anyone. Same thing all over the world.

117
00:19:46,000 --> 00:20:03,000
So I know that which my mother taught me as I get older, I know this. I'm Jesus Christ's child or whatever it is you believe in. My salvation is not about this world. It's somewhere else.

118
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:19,000
Do you know those questions you're asking in your sense of not belonging in the community? Do you remember sort of when and how you first had a sense of not belonging in the community? When that happened to you, how you understood that?

119
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:37,000
Well, first of all, they questioned my eyes. You know, you can tell a person is by racial. Mostly got the green eyes. They got those eyes. And they call me, I was a devil's child. I just spent in a good school.

120
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:56,000
Well, also, I lived exactly a mile from the school. I couldn't catch the birth of, I didn't want to fight my relatives. I walked the school a little morning. It was something about your hair. They pulled you. They did it. You're different. You know, you're not just woman. You're not getting out of here.

121
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:25,000
We still be called different marriage. So what I'm saying, what I mean, you're right about that. So what I'm saying, can I be just America? I want to be an American citizen. I don't want to be black or white. I do am out in America. You know, you know, and then you think about it within yourself and then you got to be very careful. You know, I want to offend them.

122
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:43,000
You can't be too I spoke because you don't feel someone. And I really don't want to do that. But it's very difficult when you are mixed. Very. Catch it all. It's when you're born. You know, you're different.

123
00:21:43,000 --> 00:22:02,000
They call my mother butter gal because she was blonde. And her at the time, her stepfather was her stepfather. My grandmother was raped by the plantation owner.

124
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:16,000
And when she found out she was pregnant, she ran off from it's a little area out near Prenniss, Coffinchett. And she ran off to Hattiesburg.

125
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:31,000
She worked enough to buy a house. They were selling houses from World War I off of Camp Shelby. Little shotgun houses they had down there.

126
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:45,000
And they moved them from Camp Shelby up to Hattiesburg. So there would be just lines of real shotgun, rolls of shotgun houses. They'd stick them beside the railroad track anywhere.

127
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:54,000
She married my grandmother married what they call a cagin out of Southern Louisiana.

128
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:00,000
What what what at that time? What do they what made someone a cagin?

129
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:15,000
They were Frenchmen out of originally out of Newfoundland and they you know they loaded them down, shipped them down from Newfoundland to the Louisiana territory.

130
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:25,000
And the Native Americans. And I don't know which nation the Native Americans and Africans.

131
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:42,000
And they are still calling themselves cagins. They speak with a little accent. They live in those swamps. I'm not saying they're backward to anything. It's just that they they maintain that culture.

132
00:23:42,000 --> 00:24:02,000
And my mother's father whom she called father. She sent him to my grandmother made a decision never to have another child after he was killed on the railroad. He worked on the railroad in 1932.

133
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:17,000
And that was a year when I did a little research when there were many men of color who were killed on the railroad. Now whether it was just purely accident or intentional, I don't know.

134
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:30,000
But my mother was an only child. And my grandmother would put a mole on top of her head and just cut her hair around like that and around the front.

135
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:45,000
And she would deliver the butter that my grandmother would make because my granddad had a cow, a pig that he'd keep down on the river, which was just quarter mile away.

136
00:24:45,000 --> 00:25:08,000
So for my mother, she would not talk about the fact of who she was and how she came about. It was a taboo subject. And I went looking for a birth certificate for her. And the sad thing. I can't smile on this one.

137
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:24,000
The sad thing is that she lived until she was 67 and she never knew her real name. On birth certificate, it says Christine Holloway.

138
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:52,000
They mixed my grandmother's name, which was Phanimae Holloway. They took the old, mistook the old and made it in A or just didn't care or whatever. So she was born and died and never knew her name. But her name that we knew was Alpharenzia Elsie after her daddy, out of Louisiana.

139
00:25:52,000 --> 00:26:13,000
And when we looked up Frank Elsie, she was the only child listed under him, even though he had been married before. And I don't know if there was a divorce or anything like that. It was very hard for my mother. She was like your family.

140
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:33,000
She was ostracized on both sides. If you had one drop, one 30 second, one 16, what they call black blood, you were black.

141
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:47,000
So you could be blonde and you can be blue eyed. But if there was a, as Mr. Carter would say, one in the wood pile, then you were that.

142
00:26:47,000 --> 00:27:13,000
For me, I was dark enough. The only people who mistaked me are the, some people from Thailand or some of the Hawaiian islands, Fijians, Koreans. There's some dark skinned Koreans. And I get mistaken, especially by the men, if I'm walking on the street.

143
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:34,000
And I lived, I went to school part-time in New York City. And I found that those kinds of people who would talk to me in their language. And I would say, I'm sorry, I don't understand what you're saying. It was probably good. I didn't understand.

144
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:52,000
But I know that many people, and I straight my hair at that time, I don't straight my hair anymore. I just got to where I said, I have to love me, no matter what. And I love me all over.

145
00:27:52,000 --> 00:28:18,000
I still own the property that my grandmother inherited. And so my daddy's dead. And it came to us, children. And we've maintained it. In fact, I have a daughter retiring next year. And I gave 12 acres to her. And she's going to build the house on her 12 acres.

146
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:21,000
And she's going back to the country like you.

147
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:25,000
Is anybody farm your land?

148
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:44,000
No, it's timber. But it's beautiful land. And I'm sure if you put some, my great-grandmother used to have her garden closest to the house. And then there were fields of corn and cotton and all kinds of vegetables.

149
00:28:44,000 --> 00:29:02,000
And the smokehouse. And once a year, people would get together once or twice a year. The women would get together and do all the canning. And the men would get together in the fall and make syrup and smoke meat. And the women would make sausage.

150
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:11,000
So it was more community than what you have in a city.

151
00:29:11,000 --> 00:29:16,000
You didn't have that.

152
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:35,000
Well, yes, you did. You had those, my uncle and I who had a store. But his daddy, his dad, his dad, his dad, it was Colonel Hall. Colonel Hall, Colonel Robert Hall. And my uncle Rowan were first cousins.

153
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:53,000
So him being green-eyed and very fair and blonde, he not only had the store in our village, he was even allowed to sell guns and ammunition, which was a law.

154
00:29:53,000 --> 00:30:03,000
Blacks could not own hardwares. So they could, because they could get guns and ammunition. But he was allowed because he was who he was.

155
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:18,000
That's interesting. And that family on LMA married one of my uncles on my daddy's side. And on LMA, we were blonde and blue-eyed when she died. That she was in her late 60s.

156
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:35,000
So we were just humans. And you can't afford to hate anyone because then you hate yourself. And I usually don't use black and white.

157
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:47,000
Everyone here at the university knows I don't. And I think some people do things out of guilt because I know

158
00:30:47,000 --> 00:31:16,000
